## Walk-Through: `handoff_roundtrip` E2E Test

This is the simplest end-to-end test; it exercises the full QEMU1 -> vsim -> QEMU2 path.

### The test program (`hybrid_vsim/hybrid/test/handoff_roundtrip.S`)

```asm
_start:
    csrwi   0x7C0, 0          // entry: QEMU drains state, exits
    li      a0, 1
    li      a1, 2
    add     a2, a0, a1        // a2 = 3, computed inside vsim
    csrwi   0x7C0, 1          // exit: vsim drains state, exits 200
    SEMIHOST_EXIT a2          // QEMU 2 exits with code = a2 = 3
```

Three "phases" are visible in the assembly:
- **Phase A** (runs in QEMU 1): everything before the first `csrwi`.
- **Phase B** (runs in vsim): the `add a2, a0, a1`. This is the only instruction whose cycle behavior matters.
- **Phase C** (runs in QEMU 2): the semihosting exit, which reports `a2` back to the host as the process exit code.

### The driver (`hybrid_vsim/tests/hybrid/roundtrip_e2e.sh`)

The driver script orchestrates three processes:

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant SH as roundtrip_e2e.sh
    participant Q1 as QEMU 1 + plugin
    participant VS as vsim
    participant Q2 as QEMU 2 (spawned by vsim)

    SH->>Q1: launch with -plugin libhybrid_handoff.so,outfile=state_qemu.bin
    Note over Q1: runs Phase A
    Q1->>Q1: hits csrwi 0x7C0, 0
    Q1->>SH: writes state_qemu.bin, exits cleanly

    SH->>VS: launch with --resume-from-qemu state_qemu.bin --qemu-binary qemu...
    Note over VS: DM halts core, writes regs from state_qemu.bin, sets PC, resumes
    Note over VS: runs Phase B (a2 = 1 + 2 = 3)
    VS->>VS: csr_trigger sees retire of csrwi 0x7C0, 1
    VS->>VS: drains state via DM into state_vsim.bin
    VS->>Q2: spawns qemu-system-riscv64 -gdb tcp:... -S -semihosting
    VS->>Q2: connects to gdbstub, sends 'G' packet with regs, sends 'c'
    Note over Q2: runs Phase C (semihosting exit with a2)
    Q2->>VS: process exits with code 3
    VS->>SH: vsim process exits with code 3
    SH->>SH: assert exit code == EXPECT_RC (3) -> PASS
```

### What each step proves

| Step | What it tests |
|---|---|
| QEMU 1 produces `state_qemu.bin` | The TCG plugin correctly identifies `csrwi 0x7C0, 0`, drains all GPRs/CSRs, and exits. |
| vsim resumes and computes `a2 = 3` | The JTAG DM in-process driver correctly writes 32 GPRs and sets the PC. |
| vsim drains and exits with code 200 | The retire-PC trigger fires, and the symmetric drain path works. |
| QEMU 2 exits with code 3 | The handback path (spawn QEMU + gdbstub register restore) round-trips state correctly. The test passes because the `a2` value computed inside vsim survived back into QEMU. |

If any link in the chain breaks, the final exit code will not equal 3 (the value `EXPECT_RC` the driver compares against).

## Where to Look Next

- `include/hybrid/state_abi.h` - the wire contract; both QEMU plugin and vsim include this exact header.
- `qemu_plugin/hybrid_handoff.c` - the QEMU side. Look at `resolve_handles` and the entry-trigger callback.
- `hybrid_vsim/src/hybrid/` - the vsim side: `qemu_resume.hpp`, `state_drain.hpp`, `csr_trigger.hpp`, `qemu_handback.hpp`.
- `hybrid_vsim/hybrid_plan.md` - the original design document, with full rationale for every decision.
- `run_e2e.sh` - run all e2e tests locally without going through CMake/CTest.

## Mental Model in One Sentence

> Two simulators agree on a memory map and a register struct, take turns running the same program, and use a magic CSR write as the baton-pass.
